              <tr> 
                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">Any Methods Necessary</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a4.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=1992"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=1992"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=2299">Jared "Romas" Beavers</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 2299 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">An easy way to improve your game, even if you live in the Desert Heart&#8230;</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Using the Internet to the gamer&amp;#8217;s advantage. Sounds pretty lame, right? I mean, we all know about Decktech, Decipher, and several other incredible Star Wars CCG sites; but how can you use the Internet&amp;#8217;s resources to their fullest potential? How can someone (like me) who is not used to tournament games or games in general practice without leaving the comfort of their own home? Hopefully I can answer a few of these questions.<br>
<br>
Here&amp;#8217;s the break-down of sections, so if you feel you already know most of a section, just skip on to the next. Thanks for reading.<br>
<br>
I.	Intro- What the Hades are you talking about?<br>
II.	Stuff- What&amp;#8217;s in it for Me?<br>
III.	In Depth- How do I get Started?<br>
IV.	The Process- What?<br>
V.	Darkside- There&amp;#8217;s a catch, right?<br>
<br>
<br>
I. Intro- What the Hades are you talking about?<br>
<br>
I started playing SWCCG the year Premiere came out. I was ecstatic. I had a two-player set from Wal-Mart, a couple booster packs, and no idea what I was doing. Fortunately, I had a friend (Richard) who did, and we would pick up our piles and combat each other every chance we got. Now, I know this sound&amp;#8217;s like a &amp;#8220;How I got into SWCCG&amp;#8221; article right now, but I&amp;#8217;m only setting the stage. As the saga continues, I move away, and the nearest tournament scene is a good hour and a half drive. I&amp;#8217;d never played in tournaments, so I didn&amp;#8217;t think it would bother me that bad. I was wrong. The nearest players I knew were the ones I left in my hometown. I had no one to play, and didn&amp;#8217;t want my investment to go to waste, so I began my search. What I found was astounding. I found that anyone, anywhere [with internet access] could play anything against anyone. That blew my feeble mind. That&amp;#8217;s what this article is about. Helping out the hermit player.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
II. Stuff- What&amp;#8217;s in it for Me?<br>
<br>
The advantages are endless, but I&amp;#8217;ll restrain myself to 4.<br>
<br>
A.	Variety- With online play comes not only access to more people, but more decks. Wanting to try out that new deck you created, see how it fairs against EBO or TRM? Now you have access not only to the major archetypes, but also the variations of the major archetypes: stuff you will see in those tournament games you want to play.<br>
B.	Developing Skills- While you may not have the advantage of being able to see your opponent and read his &amp;#8216;tells,&amp;#8217; you will have a chance to pick up on the basics: moving, battling, force use, when to play that all important interrupt, and when to hold back. &amp;#8220;Practice makes perfect.&amp;#8221; The more you practice, the more skills you pick up, and with the internet, you can play a two games a night if you wish, against completely different decks.<br>
C.	Convenience- You don&amp;#8217;t have to wait for a buddy to come over. You don&amp;#8217;t have to wait until the weekend to playtest. As soon as the deck pulls out of the lot, you can thrust it into competition. Not only that, but you can &amp;#8216;pretest.&amp;#8217; This can save you some money. (Hypothetical situation-) You don&amp;#8217;t have the cards you need for an incredible deck idea, but you&amp;#8217;re not sure it will work. So what do you do? Proxy. That&amp;#8217;s right, Proxy. You print out the text of the card you&amp;#8217;re missing, slide it into that extra card sleeve, and try the deck out. Doesn&amp;#8217;t work? No loss. Works well? Trade off for it. This saves you the pain of learning the hard way your deck is not all it&amp;#8217;s cracked up to be.<br>
D.	Freedom and Preparation- How much does any of this stuff cost? Absolutely free. This method can prepare you for tournaments. I&amp;#8217;m not saying it is the end all, be all of preparation methods, but it is something. It can help you keep the edge.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
III. In Depth- How do I get Started?<br>
<br>
Since you obviously have a computer and access to the Internet, you&amp;#8217;re almost ready to play. First of all, you need a deck. Very hard to play without a deck, and I mean real cards; don&amp;#8217;t go printing off a list of cards and using them when you need them. Try to keep the game as real as possible. My next suggestion is an Instant Messenger. This is the most widely accepted method of play. How you play is discussed in the next section, and is pretty simple. AOL IM is the most popular version, though ICQ and Yahoo! are also decent. And finally, you&amp;#8217;ll want a computer binder program, such as Deckmaker, Deckbuilder, or WinDeck. All of these make it more convenient for pasting information about a card, or looking up a card you don&amp;#8217; know without have to look through your collection. These are the tools of the trade. Links for nearly all materials needed are listed at the bottom of the article.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
IV. The Process- What?<br>
<br>
The card play is simple. You play a normal game, but you type everything you say, such as what you deploy, how much you activate, where you battle, who you&amp;#8217;re swingin that saber at, and when you lose {gasp} force. You have your own little table in front of you, and your opponent has his. The situation gets really hairy when inserts are played. It is an unspoken rule to check with your opponent before the game starts. If he/she says no, have a few extra cards handy to swap out. Here&amp;#8217;s a sample for you:<br>
<br>
Activate: 4<br>
Deploy: Mara Jade and Saber to the swamp (Ralltiir) for 6.<br>
Battle you there for 4 force. Interrupt! You Are Beaten your Obi.<br>
I&amp;#8217;ll swing at the scrub&amp;#8230; destinies are 1 (Lord Vader) and 6 (Emperor). He&amp;#8217;s hit&amp;#8230;<br>
Battle Destiny is 3 (Sense)&amp;#8230; Total power of 7, 3 attrition&amp;#8230;<br>
<br>
You get the picture.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
V. Darkside- There&amp;#8217;s a Catch, right?<br>
<br>
There sure is. While online playing is fun, and can help you with your game, is it completely accurate as to how your deck will fair in a tournament? Never. You see, some people take their playing a little too seriously and, because you can&amp;#8217;t see them, will cheat. It is unavoidable. There will always be cheaters out there, but the great thing is &amp;#8211; You Don&amp;#8217;t Have To Play Them--. That&amp;#8217;s right, you can just leave. Find another game. Another problem: time consumption. Because you are typing everything you do, a game could take double the length it normally would in a tournament.<br>
<br>
Although there is a downside to Internet playing, I believe it does more good than harm. It can help you keep the edge, vary your strategy, and develop those skillz. Thank again for reading, I hope this improved your game.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
~Romas<br>
AIM: romas55<br>
<br>
